(352, 'Pakistan''s infamous illicit gun makers of Dara Adamkhel are about to  be legitimised as the government prepares to build a new industrial zone  for the village''s hundreds of backyard gunsmiths.\n\n\n  Dara Adamkhel''s gunsmiths are renowned for their ability to turn out  anything from shotguns to pistols to AK-47s, as well as ammunition, from  their safe haven in Pakistan''s once-lawless Federally Administered  Tribal Areas.\n\n\n  Since government forces took control of the area from militants, they  have been able to re-introduce a program that will turn the illegal  arms-making racket into a legitimate trade with modern factories and  equipment, to supply local and international markets.\n  The transformation is being overseen by the state-run Pakistan  Hunting and Sporting Arms Development Company, which announced funding  for the new industrial business park in Dara Adamkhel.\n\n\n  The village already has 16 gun-making factories and hundreds of small  workshops, and most of the population relies on the trade, including  15,000 people employed directly in it and another 22,000 indirectly. \n\n\n  Gun making, which has been going on for more than 100 years, has supported several generations of gunsmiths and workers there. \n  Dara Adamkhel''s gunsmiths are known for their talents in copying any  gun, and it would take about 10 days for a replica of a shotgun to be  produced if the gunsmith had never seen it before, and then 3-4 days for  every subsequent copy. \n\n\n  Even before the new complex is built, the trade has made moves into  legalised arms making and several manufacturers have shown their  sporting guns at shows in Europe.\n\n\n  At least one batch of shotguns has been sold in the UK, and several  hundred pump-action and double-barrel shotguns are about to be exported  to Lebanon.\n\nCourtesy [url]http://shootingnews.com.au[/url]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, 0, '', 'on_nl2br', 0, 0, 0),
